books.title: To Kill a Mockingbird
books.author: Harper Lee
books.description: Set in the American South during the 1930s, it follows the Finch family and their community as they confront racial injustice. Through the eyes of young Scout Finch, the novel explores themes of morality, compassion, and the loss of innocence.
books.moral: To Kill a Mockingbird teaches the importance of empathy, standing up for what is right even when it's difficult, and recognizing the humanity in others regardless of race or background.

books.title: The Hobbit
books.author: J.R.R. Tolkien
books.description: Follows the hobbit Bilbo Baggins as he embarks on an unexpected adventure with a group of dwarves and the wizard Gandalf. Along the way, Bilbo discovers courage, friendship, and his own capacity for heroism.
books.moral: The Hobbit celebrates the hero's journey, the value of friendship and loyalty, and the triumph of good over evil.

books.title: Harry Potter and the Sorcerer's Stone
books.author: J.K. Rowling
books.description: Introduces readers to the wizarding world and the young Harry Potter, who discovers he is a wizard on his eleventh birthday. Harry attends Hogwarts School of Witchcraft and Wizardry, where he learns about friendship, bravery, and the power of love.
books.moral: Harry Potter and the Sorcerer's Stone emphasizes the importance of friendship, courage, and standing up against injustice.

books.title: Moby-Dick
books.author: Herman Melville
books.description: Follows the journey of Captain Ahab aboard the whaling ship Pequod as he seeks revenge on the white whale, Moby Dick, who took his leg. The novel explores themes of obsession, fate, and the power of nature.
books.moral: Moby-Dick warns against the dangers of obsession and the destructive consequences of unchecked ambition.

books.title: The Da Vinci Code
books.author: Dan Brown
books.description: Follows symbologist Robert Langdon and cryptologist Sophie Neveu as they unravel a mystery surrounding a murder in the Louvre Museum. The novel explores themes of religion, symbolism, and conspiracy.
books.moral: The Da Vinci Code encourages questioning established beliefs, exploring hidden truths, and challenging conventional wisdom.

books.title: The Alchemist
books.author: Paulo Coelho
books.description: Follows Santiago, a shepherd boy, as he embarks on a journey to fulfill his personal legend. Along the way, he learns about the importance of following one's dreams, listening to one's heart, and finding one's true purpose in life.
books.moral: The Alchemist teaches the importance of perseverance, self-discovery, and following one's dreams, and it emphasizes the transformative power of personal growth.

books.title: The Lord of the Rings: The Fellowship of the Ring
books.author: J.R.R. Tolkien
books.description: Follows Frodo Baggins and his companions as they journey across Middle-earth to destroy the One Ring and defeat the dark lord Sauron. The novel explores themes of heroism, friendship, and the struggle between good and evil.
books.moral: The Lord of the Rings celebrates the power of friendship, the triumph of good over evil, and the importance of perseverance in the face of adversity.

books.title: Gone Girl
books.author: Gillian Flynn
books.description: Tells the story of Nick and Amy Dunne, whose marriage falls apart amidst deception, betrayal, and manipulation. The novel explores themes of identity, marriage, and the nature of truth.
books.moral: Gone Girl examines the complexities of relationships, the blurred lines between truth and fiction, and the consequences of deception and manipulation.

books.title: Jane Eyre
books.author: Charlotte BrontÃ«
books.description: Follows the life of the orphaned Jane Eyre as she becomes a governess and falls in love with the brooding Mr. Rochester. The novel explores themes of love, independence, and the search for belonging.
books.moral: Jane Eyre highlights the importance of self-respect, the pursuit of independence and equality, and the power of love to overcome adversity.

books.title: The Hunger Games
books.author: Suzanne Collins
books.description: Set in a dystopian society where teenagers are forced to compete in a televised fight to the death. It follows Katniss Everdeen as she volunteers to take her sister's place in the Hunger Games and becomes a symbol of rebellion.
books.moral: The Hunger Games explores the brutality of authoritarian regimes, the resilience of the human spirit, and the importance of standing up against oppression.

data.author: George Orwell
data.description: A dystopian novel set in a totalitarian society ruled by the Party and its leader, Big Brother. It follows Winston Smith, who rebels against the oppressive regime. The novel explores themes of surveillance, manipulation, and the erosion of truth.
data.moral: 1984 serves as a warning about the dangers of totalitarianism, the importance of individual freedom, and the power of language and truth.

data.title: Brave New World
data.author: Aldous Huxley
data.description: Set in a dystopian future where society is engineered for stability and conformity. It follows Bernard Marx and John the Savage as they challenge the oppressive social order. The novel explores themes of individuality, freedom, and the cost of happiness.
data.moral: Brave New World warns against sacrificing individuality and freedom for the sake of stability and happiness, and it questions the ethics of technological and social control.

data.title: Pride and Prejudice
data.author: Jane Austen
data.description: A romantic novel set in early 19th-century England, it follows the outspoken Elizabeth Bennet and the proud Mr. Darcy as they navigate misunderstandings, societal expectations, and their own prejudices.
data.moral: Pride and Prejudice emphasizes the importance of overcoming personal biases, the complexities of love and marriage, and the pursuit of happiness and self-awareness.

data.title: The Catcher in the Rye
data.author: J.D. Salinger
data.description: Narrated by Holden Caulfield, a disenchanted teenager, as he navigates the challenges of adolescence and adulthood. The novel explores themes of alienation, identity, and the loss of innocence.
data.moral: The Catcher in the Rye highlights the struggles of adolescence, the search for authenticity in a phony world, and the importance of preserving innocence amidst societal pressures.

data.title: The Great Gatsby
data.author: F. Scott Fitzgerald
data.description: Set in the 1920s, it follows the mysterious Jay Gatsby and his pursuit of the American Dream. Through the eyes of narrator Nick Carraway, the novel explores themes of wealth, love, and the emptiness of materialism.
data.moral: The Great Gatsby examines the hollowness of the American Dream, the corrupting influence of wealth, and the impossibility of recapturing the past.
